Under key cos there is some useful information about the electoral process for that machine, including number of voters who actually voted, overvotes, undervotes, etc.

 'bo': 1,
 'v': 15,
 'tot': 6017,
 'per': '0.24',
 'ser': 'HPM180PA01059803'}

bo: a unique identifier for each candidate. bo 1-62 represent the senatorial candidates in alphabetical order; thus, bo: 1 is Vangie Abejo and bo: 62 is Cynthia Villar.
tot: total number of votes obtained by all candidates.
v: number of votes obtained by candidate referred to by bo.
per: v divided by tot. Misleading for positions with multiple seats.
ser: likely the serial number of the vote counting machine.

The following code will read the Election Result Data from the Election Return files which were downloaded from the COMELEC Transparency Server during the period May 14 to 17, 2019.

(Note: This process may take about 10 minutes to complete.)

In [5]:
results = []
vote_count_n = np.array(np.zeros(65, dtype=int))
# pattern = re.compile(r'^/.+?/results/(.+?)/(.+?)/(.+?)/(.+?)$')
empty_zone_log = ''

for root, dirs, files in \
    os.walk(results_path):
        
    if len(dirs) == 0:
        path_obj = Path(root).parts
        res = []
        # Region
        res.append(path_obj[4])
        # Province
        res.append(path_obj[5])
        # City/Municipality
        res.append(path_obj[6])
        # Barangay/Zone (optional)
        try:
            res.append(path_obj[7])
        except IndexError:
            # Pass, but count number of occurrences of this situation
            res.append('BLANK')
            log_message = f'Empty directory in {path_obj[4]}/{path_obj[5]}/{path_obj[6]}'
            empty_zone_log += log_message + '\n'
        vote_count_b = np.array(np.zeros(65, dtype=int))
        for file in files:
            if file != 'info.json':
#                 data = json.loads(open(root + '/' + file).read())
                data = json.load(open(Path(root) / file))
                data_rs = data['rs']

                vote_count = np.array(np.zeros(65, dtype=int))
                for data_bo in data_rs:
                    vote_count[int(data_bo['bo'])] += int(data_bo['v'])
                    if int(data_bo['bo']) >= 62:
                        break
                if len(data['cos']) > 5:
                    vote_count[63] = int(data['cos'][4]['ct'])
                    vote_count[64] = int(data['cos'][2]['ct'])
                vote_count_b += vote_count
        
        res.append(vote_count_b)
        results.append(res)

        vote_count_n += vote_count_b

    if map_df.iloc[c]['REGION'] == 'Metropolitan Manila':
        map_df.iloc[c]['REGION'] = 'NCR'
    else:
        match = re.match(r'^.+?\((.+?)\)', map_df.iloc[c]['REGION'])
        if match.group(1) == 'ARMM':
            map_df.iloc[c]['REGION'] = 'BARMM'
        else:
            map_df.iloc[c]['REGION'] = match.group(1).upper()

The following code loads data from the 2015 National Census. Though the result is from about 4 years ago, an assumption is made for this study that the data are still reflective of the current state of the nation (considering the addition and reduction of statistics through the years; even though it is known that the rates of the two are different).

Furthermore, the data from the 2015 National Census still include the Negros Island Region (NIR) which is no longer existing. Therefore, the data of NIR were divided according back to Region VI and VII (from Negros Occidental and Negros Oriental, respectively).

Section 3. Stories¶

Story 1. Performance by Affiliation¶

There were 62 players in the senatorial race, but the midterm elections were seen by many as a referendum on the administration of President Rodrigo Duterte, who in 2019 is at the midway point of his office term.

Two major teams emerged:

  • The Administration's Coalition Group - Hugpong ng Pagbabago (HNP)
  • Opposition Group - Otso Diretso (OTSO)

HNP's objective is to solidify the administration's rule and ensure easier passage of legislation to further their agenda.

OTSO's objective is to oppose the administration and provide a 'check-and-balance' system in the Senate against potential abuses.

Average Number of Votes Garnered per Candidate by Affiliation¶

def plot_turnout_ph(variable, merged, color):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, figsize=(10, 10))
    merged.plot(column='percent', cmap=color,
                linewidth=0.8, ax=ax, edgecolor='0.8')

    for i, point in merged.centroid.iteritems():
        if 'REGION' in i:
            reg_n = i.split()[1]
        else:
            reg_n = i
        ax.text(s=reg_n, x=point.x, y=point.y, fontsize='large')

    ax.axis('off')
    ax.set_title('Voter Turnout in Percent, By Region'.format(variable), 
                 fontdict={'fontsize': '25', 'fontweight' : '3'})
    ax.annotate('Source: COMELEC Transparency Server', xy=(0.1, .08), 
                xycoords='figure fraction', horizontalalignment='left', verticalalignment='top', fontsize=12, color='#555555')

    sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(
        cmap=color, norm=plt.Normalize(vmin=merged['percent'].min(), 
                                       vmax=merged['percent'].max()))
    sm._A = []
    cbar = fig.colorbar(sm)
    plt.show()

region_turnout_df = region_statistics['percent']*100
merged = map_df.set_index('REGION').join(region_turnout_df)

Story 4. Candidates' Performance by Region¶

As a candidate, you will want to know in which geographical areas you performed well or poorly in. Let us explore the performance of each winning candidate by region.

Winners' Heatmaps¶

Each of the winners in the election fared differently depending on the geographic region. In this section, we will explore the proportion of voters in each region that voted for each of the winners.

The proportion is calculated as follows:

\begin{equation} P = \frac{V}{N} \cdot 100% \end{equation}

where V is the actual number who voted for a particular candidate, and N is the total number of voters in that region who actually voted.

The following codes display the heatmap proportion of votes each of the Top 12 winners' votes got across the country. The darker color shows the region where the candidates got their most proportion of votes.

In [34]:
def plot_geo_ph(variable, merged, color):

#     vmin, vmax = 120, 220
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, figsize=(10, 10))
    merged.plot(column='PROP', cmap=color, linewidth=0.8, ax=ax, 
                edgecolor='0.8')

    for i, point in merged.centroid.iteritems():
        if 'REGION' in i:
            reg_n = i.split()[1]
        else:
            reg_n = i
        ax.text(s=reg_n, x=point.x, y=point.y, fontsize='large')

    ax.axis('off')
    ax.set_title(
        'Proportion, in %, of Voters who Voted for {}, by Region'\
        .format(variable), fontdict={'fontsize': '25', 'fontweight' : '3'})
    ax.annotate('Source: COMELEC Transparency Server', xy=(0.1, .08), 
                xycoords='figure fraction', horizontalalignment='left', 
                verticalalignment='top', fontsize=12, color='#555555')

#     sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap=color, 
#                                norm=plt.Normalize(vmin=merged['PROP'].min(), 
#                                                   vmax=merged['PROP'].max()))
    sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap=color, 
                               norm=plt.Normalize(vmin=0, 
                                                  vmax=100))
    sm._A = []
    cbar = fig.colorbar(sm)
    plt.show()

def plot_affil_ph(variable, merged, color, filename):

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, figsize=(10, 10))
    merged.plot(column='VOTES', cmap=color, linewidth=0.8, ax=ax, 
                edgecolor='0.8')

            reg_n = i.split()[1]
        else:

        ax.text(s=reg_n, x=point.x, y=point.y, fontsize='large')

    ax.axis('off')

                               norm=plt.Normalize(vmin=merged['VOTES'].min(),

merged = map_df.set_index('REGION').join(vote_df.set_index('REGION'))
plot_affil_ph('OTSO', merged, 'YlGn', filename='figures/otso_votes_map.png')

ANALYSIS¶

OTSO bets performed poorly in the last election. There were even regions where no OTSO bet was part of the Top 12. At most, only 4 OTSO bets were included in the Top 12 of some regions. This shows that the party (and/or its candidates) has a low reputation and popularity with the voters. If the OTSO want to gain power in 2022, they have to do something to change the voters' sentiment and awareness of the OTSO party and its mission.

Story 6. Influence of the INC¶

About 4% of the voting population of the country are members of the INC Religious Group. Though this can be considered a small group, the INC Group can be a significant force in any election if the other bigger groups are not united and do not act collectively as a group.

In [51]:

vote_df.columns = ['REGION', 'VOTES']

plot_affil_ph('INC bets', merged, 'OrRd', 'figures/inc_votes_map.png')

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(7,7))

                   for l, s in zip(labels, sizes)], loc="best")

plt.title('Senatorial Election Winners by Religious-Group Endorsed')
plt.show()

ANALYSIS¶

11 of the 12 candidates endorsed by INC Religious Group made it to the Top 12. This shows that candidates endorsed by INC tend to run successfully.

INC is another strong force during elections. Even though it is a minority group in the overall population, INC members are believed to vote collectively as guided by their leaders during elections. With the result of the recent election, 11 of the 12 candidates who the INC endorsed got into the Top 12. In the first place, the result shows that INC makes a good decision in selecting the winnable candidates. Further, INC's endorsement is considered to have an effect on the winnability of the candidate. Therefore, future candidates (as with previous election's candidates) should consider getting the endorsement of religious group especially the INC.

Story 7. The Home-Court Advantage¶

Home-Court Advantage¶

Many candidates enjoy the so-called 'Home-Court Advantage', which means that they will tend to gain more votes from the Municipalities, Provinces, and/or Regions that they reside in, or originate from.

We will take a look at how the home-court advantage worked for some selected candidates.

This code generates the Provincial Level and the City Level results of the election.

In [53]:
results_p_df = results_df.groupby(['province'])\
    .agg(dict(zip(list(range(1,65)), ['sum']*64)))
results_c_df = results_df.groupby(['city'])\
    .agg(dict(zip(list(range(1,65)), ['sum']*64)))

The following codes test the Home-Court Advantage hypothesis whether it helped the candidates during the last election.

As shown by these tests, candidates should never just rely on the home court-advantage hypothesis because it works with some but not all. As mentioned earlier, candidates should work in campaigning on all regions, provinces, cities and municipalities in the whole country and should try not to miss any (most importantly, not to skip the home court). The home court advantage works depending on the image and reputation of the candidate (and/or his/her family) and also on how deep the loyalty of the people to the candidate and/or to his/her family.
